{{Other people|Michael Jensen}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox clergy | child = | honorific_prefix = [[The Reverend]] | name = Michael Jensen<!--or: subject_name --> | honorific_suffix = | image = <!--or: image_name --> | alt = | caption = <!--or: image_caption --> | pronunciation = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} if deceased. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date --> | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | nationality =[[Australian]] | other_names = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = Clergyman, author, speaker, lecturer | years_active = | spouse = | children = | parents = [[Peter Jensen (bishop)|Peter Jensen]] | relatives = <!--or: relations, family --> | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | religion = Christianity ([[Anglicanism|Anglican]]) | church = [[Anglican Church of Australia]] | ordained = | writings = | congregations = [[St Mark's Church, Darling Point]] | offices_held = Rector, St Mark's Parish, Darling Point | title = | signature = | signature_alt = | footnotes = }}
'''Michael P. Jensen''' is an [[Australian]] clergyman, author, and lecturer. He has served as the rector in the [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican]] parish of [[St Mark's Church, Darling Point|St Mark's Church]], [[Darling Point, New South Wales|Darling Point]] since 2013;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sydneyanglicans.net/author/5244 |title=Author Bio |publisher=Sydney Anglicans |accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref> and was formerly a professor of theology at [[Moore College]], Sydney.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/michael-jensen/27292 | title=Author Bio | publisher=ABC | accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref> He is a son of the former [[Anglican Archbishop of Sydney|archbishop of Sydney]], [[The Most Reverend]] [[Peter Jensen (bish<ref>op)|Peter Jensen]]. </ref> Jensen is a prolific commentator in both religious and secular forums on a range of topics. For example, in April 2016 Jensen responded to columnist [[Peter FitzSimons|Peter FitzSimons']] criticism of [[Mormon]] rugby player [[Will Hopoate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-05/jensen-is-hopoate's-mormon-faith-fair-game-for-ridicule/7299158 |title=Is Hopoate's Mormon faith fair game for ridicule? |work=ABC Drum |date=5 April 2016 |accessdate=28 April 2016 |author=Jensen, Michael}}</ref>
On 6 May 2015 Jensen's book ''You: An Introduction'' (2008) was [[List of books banned by governments|banned]] from state schools by the [[New South Wales]] [[Department of Education and Communities (New South Wales)|Department of Education and Communities]] on the basis of a "potential risk to students in the delivery of this material, if not taught sensitively and in an age appropriate manner."<ref name=Piccoli>{{cite web|last1=Piccoli|first1=Adrian|authorlink1=Adrian Piccoli|title=Letter to His Grace the Most Reverend Dr G Davies|url=http://sydneyanglicans.net/images/uploads/Letter_SRE_180515.pdf|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> The ban was lifted 18 May 2015.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}
In September 2018, Jensen launched a podcast, With All Due Respect,<ref>https://www.eternitynews.com.au/topics/with-all-due-respect/. Retrieved 6 October 2018.</ref> which he co-hosts with Megan Powell du Toit, a Baptist minister. The podcast is the first one for Eternity News, an Australian Christian news site.<ref>https://www.eternitynews.com.au/culture/the-podcast-trying-to-teach-you-how-to-have-better-conversations/. Retrieved 6 October 2018.</ref>
On 27 November 2018, Jensen published a widely panned opinion piece comparing John Allen Chau favourably to Jesus.<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/world/asia/like-jesus-us-missionary-accepted-death-as-the-price-of-reaching-out-20181127-p50ik3.html?</ref> Chau was a US missionary killed by the protected North Sentinelese tribe after travelling illegally and trespassing onto their island. In doing so, Chau risked wiping out the tribe by possibly introducing deadly pathogens the tribe had no immunity to. Jensen argued that Chau was "not attempting to ... "civilise" them" by hoping to introduce Christianity to the tribe, but only "came to save".<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/world/asia/like-jesus-us-missionary-accepted-death-as-the-price-of-reaching-out-20181127-p50ik3.html?</ref>
==Books== * [https://www.bloomsbury.com/au/tt-clark-reader-in-theological-anthropology-9780567655578/ "A T&T Clark Reader in Theological Anthropology" (Bloomsbury, 2017)] * ''Is Forgiveness Really Free?'' (The Good Book Co, 2013) * ''Pieces of Eternity'' (Acorn, 2013) * ''My God, My God - Is it Possible to Believe Anymore?'' (Cascade, 2012) * ''Sydney Anglicanism: An Apology'' (Wipf & Stock, 2012) * ''True Feelings: Perspectives on emotions in Christian life and ministry'' (Inter-Varsity Press, 2012) * ''Martyrdom and Identity: The Self on Trial'' (T&T Clark, 2010) * ''You: An Introduction'' (Matthias Media, 2008)
